{"key":"post-9022806","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9022806</id>\n<content>Calcium carbonate(ground limestone) is of little benefit to casing layers because by the time it goes to work in a few weeks, the lifespan of your casing layer is already passed.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You want hydrated lime, and you want to use it no more than one teaspoon of lime per cup of peatmoss unless you have a way of testing pH.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Gypsum is used for totally different reasons and will alter pH very little.&amp;nbsp; I'd suggest using gypsum at up to 10% of the amount of peat by volume.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9022993</next>\n<prev>9022769</prev>\n<first>9021646</first>\n<last>9023707</last>\n<when>1223047389</when>\n<utime>10/03/08 06:23 PM</utime>\n</post>"}